entry.title: [Extensions] Modify some Automation API tests to use service workers.
entry.content:
Because tests for service worker-based extensions must have a

background page, this CL rearranges these tests as follows:



1. Instead of loading an HTML page that loads a common script and the

test script, a custom extension is generated with all of the common

code in the main background page script.



2. The main background page then loads the test JS file using

chrome.test.loadScript.



3. The test script then calls into a common function with an array

of test functions to be run.



This has the advantage of avoiding the creation of separate test

extensions in chrome/test/data/extensions/api_test/automation and

only requires minor tweaks to the test JS file. The common JS file

and the html files that previously were used to launch the tests are

deleted.

entry.title: Fix SitePerProcessBrowserTests affected by isolated, sandboxed iframes.
entry.content:
The SitePerProcessBrowserTest test suite contains three tests where the

use of sandboxed frames changes the output from DepictFrameTree due to

(1) the inclusion of port numbers in sandboxed origins, and (2) entries

from soon-to-be-deleted RenderFrameHosts still being around at the time

that DepictFrameTree is called. Also, due to the additional origins

caused by the sandboxed frames, labels in the DepictFrameTree output

(which are designed to remain unique across the entire test) can

change when IsolateSandboxedIframes is enabled.



This CL updates the affected tests to address all of these issue.

DepictFrameTree was modified to suppress port numbers in site

descriptions, expected output for per-site and per-origin modes was

added, and RenderFrameHostDeleted observers were added when

needed (this varies depending on which isolation mode, if any, is

in use). Per-document expected output will be added in a future

CL, and the tests will be parameterized to run all modes.

entry.title: Fire the navigate event earlier for cross-document traversals
entry.content:
This earlier timing ensures that we fire the navigate event in the old

document when a traversal is served from the bfcache, and is more consistent with non-history cross-document navigate events.



Currently, cross-document traversals fire the navigate event at the

last possible time: during commit in the renderer, the navigate event

is fired in the old document immediately before it is unloaded. The

navigate event is not allowed to cancel or intercept a cross-document

traversal, otherwise this timing would be too late. We did not

reach a firm conclusion on when to fire the navigate event for

cross-document traversals during the design of the Navigation API

(see https://github.com/WICG/navigation-api/issues/207), and this

was the latest of the options considered.



This timing has two problems:

1. Traversals served by the back forward cache don't "commit". So

the navigate event is erroneously omitted.

2. The navigate event fires after redirects, where for other

cross-document navigations, it fires before redirects.



This CL adds plumbing for the browser to trigger the navigate event

to fire in the renderer in the cross-document traversal case, and

moves the time of the navigate event earlier. It now fires after

the browser process has decided to allow the traversal to start

(i.e., after beforeunload has been fired in any relevant frames, and

after start throttles). In the cross-document traversal case where

the navigation is not served from bfcache, this will fire the

navigate event in parallel with the network request (which is ok

because the navigate event can't intercept or cancel the navigation,

this timing would not be permissible for other navigation types where

the navigate event has more power over the navigation). In the case

where no network request is needed (bfcache, about:blank, etc.), the

navigate event task gets sent to the renderer immediately before the

commit/activation task.

entry.content:
Adds two new tables:

1. lockout_debugging_only_report, which is used to lock out the browser

from sending more debugging only reports, in a period after one

was sent.

2. cooldown_debugging_only_report, which is used to set a cooldown for

ad tech origins if they called `forDebuggingOnly` API. The duration

field is set to integer (enum) since we want to map it to finch

controlled durations in C++, and only store the duration type in

the table.

entry.title: Add OnViewHierarchyWillBeDeleted to ViewObserver
entry.content:
This notification will be useful for tracking when the entire

hierarchy will be deleted. An example use case is for UI code built

with MVC that need to ensure that the view controller does not access

destroyed views. Most of the time once the view hierarchy destruction starts we don't want to touch child views even if they technically

aren't destroyed yet. The current OnViewIsDeleting will only be triggered after child views have already been deleted. This allows for

dropping child view pointers before destruction and avoid dangling

pointers without needing to track each individual child view.

entry.title: [RWS] Introduce SetsMutation type to uphold invariants
entry.content:
This does not change any behavior; it just introduces a new type that

serves as a "proof" of the invariants that

GlobalFirstPartySets::ComputeConfig relies on. This makes the

FirstPartySetParser more directly responsible for ensuring those

invariants hold.



(A side benefit of this is that if the parser ever fails to ensure

those invariants, now the stacktrace will implicate the parser

directly, since the parser is what now creates the SetsMutation. We

can take advantage of this by writing a new fuzzer to verify that the

parser ensures these properties; this will be done in a followup CL.)

entry.title: FLEDGE: Fix race w/additional bids but no regular bids.
entry.content:
If the promise for additional bids resolved before StartBiddingAndScoringPhase, the call to DecodeAdditionalBidsIfReady() would clear encoded_signed_additional_bids_ but bid_states_for_additional_bids_ would not be filled yet, so MayHaveAdditionalBids() would return false, and without regular bids we would not request the seller worklet, stalling the auction.

Fix it by keeping track of this with an additional bool.



Also remove bogus DCHECK from InterestGroupAuctionReporter how not

having regular bids is impossible (which is what this change started

as).

entry.title: Make periodic logs synchronous when shutting down
entry.content:
Full context:

Currently, we finalize periodic logs asynchronously. This includes

things like serializing the log. Once that's done, a "reply task" is

posted back on the main thread to store that finalized log in Local

State.



One possible issue is that while the background task to finalize the

log is running, the user may shut down the browser. When this happens,

the "reply task" is never run, so the finalized log is lost. For this

reason, we don't do "delta snapshots" in the background task, since

that could lead to data loss. For example, say we did "delta

snapshots" in the background, which removes the histogram samples from

the underlying storage. If the browser was shut down by the user and

the finalized log was never stored, then the samples would be lost.

Instead, in the background task, we take a snapshot of the samples

(without removing them from the underlying storage) and fill them into

the log. We only remove the samples from the underlying when we're

back on the main thread and stored the finalized log in Local State.



There is a feature to change this behaviour:

"MetricsServiceDeltaSnapshotInBg". When enabled, this performs full

"delta snapshots" in the background task (i.e. samples are removed

from the underlying storage and filled into the log). To make sure

there is no data loss, before the background task is posted, we create

a "ScopedKeepAlive", which forces the browser to stay alive (process

won't shut down). We destroy the ScopedKeepAlive after we're back on

the main thread and stored the finalized log in Local State.



However, according to crbug.com/1490916, there can be a short period

of time where we try to create a periodic ongoing log, but the browser

shutdown has already started. When this happens, creating a

ScopedKeepAlive triggers a CHECK. This CL makes it so that if shutdown

has already started, instead of creating a ScopedKeepAlive, do the

work synchronously instead.



This solution was discussed with in scheduler-dev:

https://groups.google.com/a/chromium.org/g/scheduler-dev/c/A1d7c-sGMmk/m/jWkM5Dh3AwAJ



And seems like a similar solution already exists in Sync:

https://source.chromium.org/chromium/chromium/src/+/main:chrome/browser/background_sync/background_sync_delegate_impl.cc;l=63-68;drc=142b92dd3032947a049d244cded805617ea9b994





Bug: 1464694,1490916
